evidence: X-rays have much shorter wavelengths, roughly from 0.1 nanometers to 10 nanometers, and much higher energy.
Because X-ray photons carry so much energy, they can break molecular bonds in biological tissues.
Patients receive higher cumulative doses, and this raises public health questions.
So, it is crucial to focus on how we can reduce radiation dose and how we measure it in the first place.
